ELI LILLY INVESTS $20 MILLION IN BRAZIL

At the end of December Eli Lilly & Co announced $20 million investments
in its Brazilian subsidiary. The funding will be used to build a new
production unit alongside its existing installations in Cosmopolis, Sao
Paulo. The new plant will produce principally antibiotics.

Eli Lilly plans to double its exports from Brazil to $30 million in the
next three years. Its export markets are Mercosur (the South American
common market consisting of Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay),
Asia and the US.

This is the largest investment made by the company in Brazil where it
has been established for 51 years. Most of the $20 million will be used
to buy high technology equipment in order to bring production
techniques into line with FDA requirements.

The Brazilian subsidiary of Eli Lilly had a turnover of approximately
$180 million in 1995.

Investments reported to be planned by other companies include Knoll
Basf ($37 million); Sanofi Winthrop ($7.3 million); Fundacao Ataulfo de
Paiva ($5 million); Laboratorio Darrow ($3 million ) and Bravet ($2
million).



